==Old English==
===Etymology===
From an older form ''heorot'', from Common Germanic *''[[herutaz]]'', from Indo-European ''*kerud-'' (Greek [[κορυδος]] ‘crested lark’), from ''*ker-, *kerə-'' (Latin [[cervus]] ‘horn’).  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon ''hirot'' (Dutch ''[[hert]]''), Old High German ''[[hiruz]]'' (German ''[[Hirsch]]''), Old Norse ''[[hjǫrtr]]'' (Swedish ''[[hjort]]'').
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /heort/
===Noun===
'''heort''' ''m''

# a [[hart]] or [[stag]]

